I would come back for a special occasion sometime. Prices are fair, and we left feeling quite full!

9.2/10!

During our recent stay at Le Mount Stephen Hotel in Montreal, we had the pleasure of dining at Bar George, and it was an unforgettable experience.

The highlight of the meal was undoubtedly the Beef Wellington. Cooked to perfection, the beef was tender and flavorful, wrapped in a flaky pastry that added just the right amount of texture.

We also enjoyed a refreshing salad with watermelon that offered a delightful contrast of flavors and textures—definitely a standout dish that complemented the main course. The coffee was fantastic—rich and aromatic, making for a perfect pairing with the desserts.
The ambiance of Bar George is elegant yet inviting, making it a perfect spot for a memorable dining experience. Highly recommended for anyone visiting Montreal!

text.text:
If you're visiting Montreal and have an appreciation for historic architecture and exceptional dining experiences, Bar George is an absolute must. Nestled within the beautiful Le Mount Stephen hotel, this restaurant offers a unique blend of old-world charm and modern culinary excellence that truly sets it apart.

The experience at Bar George is nothing short of superb. From the moment you step inside, you're transported to another era, with the stunning woodwork, intricate ceilings, and luxurious ambiance reflecting the grandeur of a bygone age. It's the kind of place that makes you feel as though you've stepped into a piece of history, making it all the more special in a world where such architectural treasures are increasingly rare.

The menu, priced at a very reasonable 55 CAD, offers a delightful selection of dishes that showcase the best of British and Québécois influences. Whether you're in the mood for something hearty or something light, there's something here for every palate. The flavors are well-balanced, and the presentation is exquisite, making every meal feel like a special occasion.

What truly sets Bar George apart, however, is the service. The staff are attentive, knowledgeable, and genuinely invested in ensuring you have a memorable experience. Their warmth and professionalism add an extra layer of enjoyment to the meal, making you feel both welcome and well-cared for.

In summary, Bar George is a gem in the heart of Montreal that offers not only a fantastic dining experience but also a chance to revel in the beauty of classic architecture. Whether you're a local or just visiting, it's a place that deserves a spot on your must-visit list.

TOURIST TRAP
Service is good. Waiters and very kind, attentive, and sweet!
However, the food is atrocious. You’re honestly better off buying a frozen meal and heating it up in a microwave.
The appetizers we ordered: caprese, meatballs, and calamari were all good, though not as warm as we would’ve desired (plates were cold).
It was the main courses that really nailed the coffin shut. For starters, all the items were room temperature. The lamb shank is bland apart from the sauce reduction. It was chewy, and not cooked to order. The lasagna should really be called a soup. It is not a traditional layered lasagna in which meat sauce is between the layers of pasta. Instead, here you’ll receive layered pasta with nothing in between, placed in a bowl of meat sauce, and topped with a floating layer of cheese. The veal was tasteless apart from the taste of what felt like a cup of lemon juice it had been cooked in. The breading it seemed to have was mushy and peeled off of the veal. The one who ordered it stated they would “avoid it at all costs.”
This food is so horrible it is beyond words. At most, stick with the bread and oil.
An incredible amount of room for improvement!

text.text: It hits five stars for what it does really well, but context is important. This is an excellent experience, a journey through the terroir palette of Quebec. This makes it special. Dishes are visually stimulating and the service protocol is at the top of restauranteurs - the staff are true professionals. I opted for the seven course meal - there were a number of exceptional flavours and pairings, but a few that fell short of « wow » which is not to be mistaken for anything less than a high standard. These components of the experience - and that’s what it should be considered, an experience - create a certain value (including when the bill comes $$$$). Though, if you were to isolate for flavour on its own, there are moments that create questions. Overall, I left satisfied, content and appreciative of the experience, but reflective of the cost/experience factors. If you appreciate the visual and experiential art of a high end dinner to the fullest, it’s not to be missed. If you experience food from a more pragmatic or face value perspective, you may want to bypass the multi-course menu and select an à la carte option.
